Of course. So what we were really looking at is it's a randomized controlled trial with high risk patients for HIV-freebulation, also HIV-freebulation-related stroke.

7
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:25,000
And what we did is we gave 220 patients a smartwatch for six months and the other half of the patients did not wear a smartwatch and we found a full fourfold increase in AF diagnosis.

8
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:38,000
So nuance at AF in the intervention group wearing the smartwatch compared to the control group. And we also saw that they were diagnosed earlier than the patients in the control group.

9
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:48,000
So what does the study mean for our patients and our clinicians, do they should do something differently or?

10
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:56,000
What was mainly I think new about our project because these smartwatches have been detecting AF-freebulation for about a few years now.

11
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:14,000
We integrated it into a clinical workflow and I think that works very well. So we were able to detect AF-freebulation within 24 hours because all of the ECGs that are sent in by the patients when they experienced symptoms of anything or they received an irregular notification.

12
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:32,000
So irregular rhythm notification by the device. That's when they recorded an ECG and within 24 hours the E-health team were able to look at these ECGs and to see if AF-freebulation occurred.

13
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:54,000
This workflow worked very well. So in the Netherlands this may be quite easy to do because it's already working. And I would suggest that this would be a really good way to to monitor patients above 65 who are at high risk of both at your regulation and AF-related strong.

14
00:02:54,000 --> 00:03:09,000
